e classical composers]]\n[[Category:Italian male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Italian music arrangers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Rome]]\n[[Category:Nastro d'Argento winners]]\n[[Category:Spaghetti Western composers]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records artists]]\n", "name_user": "Bossrat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife and career:'owing to' is recommended by Fowler, instead of 'due to' and gerund to avoid the dangling participle (\"nanny's\")", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ennio_Morricone"}
{"title_page": "Keeping the Dream Alive", "text_new": "{{other uses|Keep the Dream Alive (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Keeping the Dream Alive <br><small>(So lang' man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann)</small>\n| cover    = Keeping_the_Dream_Alive_-_Freiheit.jpg\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = [[M\u00fcnchener Freiheit]]\n| album    = [[Fantasy (M\u00fcnchener Freiheit album)|Fantasy]]\n| released = 1988\n| format   =\n| recorded =\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length   = 4:09\n| label    = [[Columbia Records|CBS]]\n| writer   = Aron Strobel, Stefan Zauner (music), Timothy Touchton and Curtis Briggs (lyrics)\n| producer = Armand Volker\n}}\n\"'''Keeping the Dream Alive'''\" is a 1988 song by German pop and rock band [[M\u00fcnchener Freiheit]] - also known as Freiheit in English-speaking countries - taken from their album ''[[Fantasy (M\u00fcnchener Freiheit album)|Fantasy]]''. The music was written by Aron Strobel and Stefan Zauner with lyrics by Timothy Touchton and Curtis Briggs, and the song was arranged by Andrew Powell, Armand Volker and Stefan Zauner. It was recorded in [[Abbey Road Studios]] and mastered by Tonstudio Rico Sonderegger, with Volker as the producer. The performance by M\u00fcnchener Freiheit with the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] included featuring of additional vocals by the Jackson Singers. \n\nThe song was originally recorded in [[German language|German]] as \"So lang' man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann\", and appeared on the album ''[[Fantasie (M\u00fcnchener Freiheit album)|Fantasie]]''. It was translated into English and recorded again to be released on CBS. \n\nAn instrumental version under the original German-language title \"So lang' man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann\" appeared in 1987 on ''Schenk Mir Eine Nacht - Ihre Sch\u00f6nsten Lovesongs''.\n\nThe song's chorus bears a striking resemblance to \"All Through the Night\", a 1984 hit by [[Cyndi Lauper]].\n\n==Charts==\nIt remains the band's only international hit, peaking at #14 in the UK Charts.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 214| title-link= British Hit Singles & Albums\n}}</ref> Because it is the only charting hit of the band in the UK, it is generally considered as a [[one-hit wonder]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1988-89)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|55\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|20|song=Keeping the Dream Alive|accessdate=July 16, 2019}}\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/25210/freiheit/ |title=Official Charts Company |website=Officialcharts.com |date=1988-12-10 |accessdate=2019-03-31}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|}\n\n==Tracklist==\n===German===\n*Side A: So lang\u2019 man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann\" (Long Version) (6:58)\n*Side B:<br>\n**\"So lang\u2019 man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann\" (Instrumental Version) (4:14)\n**\"So lang\u2019 man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann\" (Single Version) (4:14)\n\n===English===\n'''Single'''\n*Side A: \"Keeping the Dream Alive\" (Single Version) (4:09)\n*Side B: \"The Land of Fantasy\" (4:51)\n\n'''Maxi single'''\n#\"Keeping the Dream Alive\" (Single Version) (4:09)\n#\"Keeping the Dream Alive\" (Extended Version) (6:31)\n#\"The Land of Fantasy\" (4:51)\n\n==Popularity==\nDue to its December release and rich orchestral sound, \"Keeping the Dream Alive\" still receives a lot of airplay at Christmas time in the United Kingdom, and can be found on many Christmas compilation albums. It is also very popular with choirs throughout the world. The song has often been mistaken for a [[The Beatles|Beatles]] track, with [[Paul McCartney]] singing lead, while the orchestra has been likened to [[Electric Light Orchestra|ELO]].<ref>[http://www.thefreelibrary.com/My+idea+to+attract+an+indifferent+nation+to+the+festival.-a0218379887 The Free Library: My idea to attract an indifferent nation to the festival]</ref><ref>[http://www.deseretnews.com/article/56825/GERMAN-BAND-FREIHEIT-IS-LATEST-TO-TRY-REVIVING-SOUND-OF-THE-BEATLES.html?pg=all German band Freiheit is the latest to try reviving sound of The Beatles]</ref> \n\nThe song failed to chart in the United States when it was originally released, gaining favour with the American public only after it was featured in the soundtrack for the movie ''[[Say Anything...]]''. The single has received additional exposure in the United States thanks to the singing talent contest ''[[American Idol]]'' on the Fox television network. The song has been used in various seasons of the show as a backdrop to video montages featuring contestants on the programme. In [[American Idol (season 9)|season 9]] of the show, the Top 12 finalists performed it on ''Idol Gives Back''.\n\n==Covers and remixes==\nThere have been a number of covers of the song both in English and in German. The German version \"So lang' man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann\" include those by [[Erkan Aki]] (2001), the [[Blassportgruppe]] (2010), and [[Annett Louisan]] (2016) and [[Heinz Rudolf Kunze]] (2016).<ref>[https://cover.info/en/search/?q=So%20lang%27%20man%20Tr%C3%A4ume%20noch%20leben%20kann CoverInfo.de website: Solang' man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann ]</ref> \n\nIn 2008, the song was remixed on the 2008 edition of ''Essential Summer Remixes'' by the Summer Remixers and released by Music Factory Entertainment Group, Ltd.<ref>[https://itunes.apple.com/tt/album/essential-summer-remixed/id283884106 Apple Music: Essential Summer Remixed]</ref>\n\nThe classic music band [[Adoro (band)|Adoro]] made up of Peter Dasch (bass-baritone), Nico M\u00fcller (baritone), Jandy Ganguly (baritone), Assaf Kacholi (lyric tenor) and Laszlo Maleczky (tenor) - presented a classical cover on their 2012 album ''Tr\u00e4ume''.\n\nIn 2013, English pop singer [[Kim Wilde]] covered it on her album ''[[Wilde Winter Songbook]]'' but only in the deluxe edition of the album.\n\nIn 2018, British pop music group [[The Fizz]] covered it in their album ''Christmas with The Fizz!''.\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe song was featured on the soundtrack of the 1989 movie ''[[Say Anything...]]'' directed by [[Cameron Crowe]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1988 songs]]\n[[Category:1988 singles]]\n[[Category:Christmas songs]]\n", "text_old": ":''For other uses, see [[Keep the Dream Alive (disambiguation)|Keep the Dream Alive]]''\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Keeping the Dream Alive <br><small>(So lang' man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann)</small>\n| cover    = Keeping_the_Dream_Alive_-_Freiheit.jpg\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = [[M\u00fcnchener Freiheit]]\n| album    = [[Fantasy (M\u00fcnchener Freiheit album)|Fantasy]]\n| released = 1988\n| format   =\n| recorded =\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length   = 4:09\n| label    = [[Columbia Records|CBS]]\n| writer   = Aron Strobel, Stefan Zauner (music), Timothy Touchton and Curtis Briggs (lyrics)\n| producer = Armand Volker\n}}\n\"'''Keeping the Dream Alive'''\" is a 1988 song by German pop and rock band [[M\u00fcnchener Freiheit]] - also known as Freiheit in English-speaking countries - taken from their album ''[[Fantasy (M\u00fcnchener Freiheit album)|Fantasy]]''. The music was written by Aron Strobel and Stefan Zauner with lyrics by Timothy Touchton and Curtis Briggs, and the song was arranged by Andrew Powell, Armand Volker and Stefan Zauner. It was recorded in [[Abbey Road Studios]] and mastered by Tonstudio Rico Sonderegger, with Volker as the producer. The performance by M\u00fcnchener Freiheit with the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] included featuring of additional vocals by the Jackson Singers. \n\nThe song was originally recorded in [[German language|German]] as \"So lang' man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann\", and appeared on the album ''[[Fantasie (M\u00fcnchener Freiheit album)|Fantasie]]''. It was translated into English and recorded again to be released on CBS. \n\nAn instrumental version under the original German-language title \"So lang' man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann\" appeared in 1987 on ''Schenk Mir Eine Nacht - Ihre Sch\u00f6nsten Lovesongs''.\n\nThe song's chorus bears a striking resemblance to \"All Through the Night\", a 1984 hit by [[Cyndi Lauper]].\n\n==Charts==\nIt remains the band's only international hit, peaking at #14 in the UK Charts.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 214| title-link= British Hit Singles & Albums\n}}</ref> Because it is the only charting hit of the band in the UK, it is generally considered as a [[one-hit wonder]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1988-89)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|55\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|20|song=Keeping the Dream Alive|accessdate=July 16, 2019}}\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/25210/freiheit/ |title=Official Charts Company |website=Officialcharts.com |date=1988-12-10 |accessdate=2019-03-31}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|}\n\n==Tracklist==\n===German===\n*Side A: So lang\u2019 man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann\" (Long Version) (6:58)\n*Side B:<br>\n**\"So lang\u2019 man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann\" (Instrumental Version) (4:14)\n**\"So lang\u2019 man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann\" (Single Version) (4:14)\n\n===English===\n'''Single'''\n*Side A: \"Keeping the Dream Alive\" (Single Version) (4:09)\n*Side B: \"The Land of Fantasy\" (4:51)\n\n'''Maxi single'''\n#\"Keeping the Dream Alive\" (Single Version) (4:09)\n#\"Keeping the Dream Alive\" (Extended Version) (6:31)\n#\"The Land of Fantasy\" (4:51)\n\n==Popularity==\nDue to its December release and rich orchestral sound, \"Keeping the Dream Alive\" still receives a lot of airplay at Christmas time in the United Kingdom, and can be found on many Christmas compilation albums. It is also very popular with choirs throughout the world. The song has often been mistaken for a [[The Beatles|Beatles]] track, with [[Paul McCartney]] singing lead, while the orchestra has been likened to [[Electric Light Orchestra|ELO]].<ref>[http://www.thefreelibrary.com/My+idea+to+attract+an+indifferent+nation+to+the+festival.-a0218379887 The Free Library: My idea to attract an indifferent nation to the festival]</ref><ref>[http://www.deseretnews.com/article/56825/GERMAN-BAND-FREIHEIT-IS-LATEST-TO-TRY-REVIVING-SOUND-OF-THE-BEATLES.html?pg=all German band Freiheit is the latest to try reviving sound of The Beatles]</ref> \n\nThe song failed to chart in the United States when it was originally released, gaining favour with the American public only after it was featured in the soundtrack for the movie ''[[Say Anything...]]''. The single has received additional exposure in the United States thanks to the singing talent contest ''[[American Idol]]'' on the Fox television network. The song has been used in various seasons of the show as a backdrop to video montages featuring contestants on the programme. In [[American Idol (season 9)|season 9]] of the show, the Top 12 finalists performed it on ''Idol Gives Back''.\n\n==Covers and remixes==\nThere have been a number of covers of the song both in English and in German. The German version \"So lang' man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann\" include those by [[Erkan Aki]] (2001), the [[Blassportgruppe]] (2010), and [[Annett Louisan]] (2016) and [[Heinz Rudolf Kunze]] (2016).<ref>[https://cover.info/en/search/?q=So%20lang%27%20man%20Tr%C3%A4ume%20noch%20leben%20kann CoverInfo.de website: Solang' man Tr\u00e4ume noch leben kann ]</ref> \n\nIn 2008, the song was remixed on the 2008 edition of ''Essential Summer Remixes'' by the Summer Remixers and released by Music Factory Entertainment Group, Ltd.<ref>[https://itunes.apple.com/tt/album/essential-summer-remixed/id283884106 Apple Music: Essential Summer Remixed]</ref>\n\nThe classic music band [[Adoro (band)|Adoro]] made up of Peter Dasch (bass-baritone), Nico M\u00fcller (baritone), Jandy Ganguly (baritone), Assaf Kacholi (lyric tenor) and Laszlo Maleczky (tenor) - presented a classical cover on their 2012 album ''Tr\u00e4ume''.\n\nIn 2013, English pop singer [[Kim Wilde]] covered it on her album ''[[Wilde Winter Songbook]]'' but only in the deluxe edition of the album.\n\nIn 2018, British pop music group [[The Fizz]] covered it in their album ''Christmas with The Fizz!''.\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe song was featured on the soundtrack of the 1989 movie ''[[Say Anything...]]'' directed by [[Cameron Crowe]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1988 songs]]\n[[Category:1988 singles]]\n[[Category:Christmas songs]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Standardized hatnote", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keeping_the_Dream_Alive"}
{"title_page": "Apparatus of the Government of Russia", "text_new": "{{Politics of Russia}}\n'''Apparatus of the Government of the Russian Federation ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043f\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438}})''' is a governmental body formed to ensure the activities of the [[Government of Russia|Government of the Russian Federation]] and the [[Prime Minister of Russia]] and to monitor the implementation of [[Order of the Government of Russia|orders and resolutions]] adopted by the Government.\n\n==History==\nOn October 19, 1905, the Council of Ministers of the Russian Empire was formed for the general \"management and consolidation of the actions of the chief heads of departments in the subjects of both legislation and higher public administration.\" The body received an independent status and the right to make key decisions, whereas in the previous format it was an advisory body to the Emperor and met by his order. The Council of Ministers began to meet weekly, the results were recorded in special magazines. The Council was headed not by the emperor, but by one of the ministers<ref name=\"\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0411\u041f\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prlib.ru/history/pages/item.aspx?itemid=948|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u043c\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0438|publisher=[[\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0431\u0438\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043e\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0430 \u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u0411. \u041d. \u0415\u043b\u044c\u0446\u0438\u043d\u0430]]|accessdate=2013-06-12|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6HKeLoNYn?url=http://www.prlib.ru/history/pages/item.aspx?itemid=948|archivedate=2013-06-12}}</ref>..\n\nThe clerical work was carried out by the permanent office, which was headed by the managing director of the Council of Ministers<ref name=\"\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0411\u041f\" />.\n\nOn February 27, 1917, the Council of Ministers ceased operations during the February Revolution. On March 2 of the same year, the Provisional Government was formed, on the day of the abdication of Nicholas II from the throne. Accordingly, the Office of the Council of Ministers was renamed the Office of the Provisional Government. The first managing director was a member of the State Duma of the first convocation Vladimir Dmitrievich Nabokov, and the position of assistant to the UD was held by Vladimir Vasilievich Nikitin \u043d<ref>\u041a\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0435\u043b\u044f\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430; \u0421\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043e \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0435 \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430, \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0414\u0443\u043c\u044b .- 1917 .- 45 \u043b. .- (\u041a\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0435\u043b\u044f\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 : 1917\u00a0\u0433.) .- \u041d\u2116\u00a05377\u0447.1; \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a: \u0413\u0410\u0420\u0424\n\u0425\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435: \u0424.1779 \u041e\u043f.1 \u0414.2</ref>. The business manager was obliged not only to organize the work of the Provisional Government, ensuring the holding of its meetings, but also to carry out activities to bring the decisions made to the public.\n\nOn October 27, 1917, the Council of People's Commissars was formed. The office was renamed to business administration and for a long time kept its name. On July 6, 1923, the Council of People's Commissars of the USSR became the highest executive body. In 1946, transformed into the Council of Ministers of the USSR.\n\nSimultaneously with the union government, the government of Russia (RSFSR) acted. In 1917-1946, under the name of the Council of People's Commissars of the RSFSR, and since 1946 - the Council of Ministers of the RSFSR.\n\nOn August 3, 1979, the RSFSR Law On the Council of Ministers of the RSFSR was adopted, in which a separate article (34) was devoted to the Office of the Council of Ministers of the RSFSR<ref>[[s:\u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0420\u0421\u0424\u0421\u0420 \u043e\u0442 03.08.1979 \u00ab\u041e \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0435 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0420\u0421\u0424\u0421\u0420\u00bb|\u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0420\u0421\u0424\u0421\u0420 \u043e\u0442 3 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0430 1979 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u00ab\u041e \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0435 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0420\u0421\u0424\u0421\u0420\u00bb]]</ref>.. The apparatus of the Government was the administration of the affairs of the Council of Ministers of the RSFSR, preparing issues for consideration by the Council of Ministers of the RSFSR and providing a systematic verification of the implementation of decisions of the CPSU (until March 14, 1990) and the Government. The business manager was a member of the Council of Ministers.\n\nBy decree of the President of the RSFSR of November 6, 1991 No. 172, the apparatus of the Government of the RSFSR and which was included as an independent structural unit in the administration of the president of the RSFSR<ref>{{cite web|url=http://graph.document.kremlin.ru/page.aspx?1219584|title=\u0423\u043a\u0430\u0437 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u0421\u0424\u0421\u0420 \u043e\u0442 06.11.1991 \u2116 172 \"\u041e\u0431 \u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u044b \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0420\u0421\u0424\u0421\u0420 \u0432 \u0443\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u044b\"|publisher=\u041e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u0424|accessdate=2013-06-12|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811190148/http://graph.document.kremlin.ru/page.aspx?1219584|archivedate=2014-08-11}}</ref> (actually expired on January 10, 1993 with the beginning of the work of the Office of the Council of Ministers of the Russian Federation<ref name=\"n2\">[http://base.consultant.ru/cons/cgi/online.cgi?req=doc;base=EXP;n=224834 \u0423\u043a\u0430\u0437 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u0424 \u043e\u0442 10.01.1993 \u2116 2]</ref>, \u043e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e \u043e\u0442\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0435\u043d 4 \u0444\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044f 1993 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430<ref>\u0423\u043a\u0430\u0437 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u0424 \u043e\u0442 4 \u0444\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044f 1993 \u2116 180</ref>, was officially canceled on February 4, 1993<ref>[[s:\u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0412\u0421 \u0420\u0424 \u043e\u0442 22.12.1992 \u2116 4175-1|\u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043e\u0442 22 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044f 1992 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u2116\u00a04175-1 \u00ab\u041e \u043f\u043e\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043a\u0435 \u0432\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0435 \u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u201e\u041e \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0435 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u00a0\u2014 \u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\u201c\u00bb]]</ref>). The leadership of the Government apparatus was entrusted to the First Deputy Chairman of the Government (until November 11, 1991, when the head of the apparatus was appointed, who was not part of the government by position).\n\nAt the same time, the law \u201cOn the Council of Ministers of the RSFSR\u201d formally continued to operate, which was recognized as invalid only in January 1993, in connection with the adoption of the law \u201cOn the Council of Ministers - the Government of the Russian Federation\u201d (the law was adopted in December 1992, but entered by virtue of January 12, 1993, after the Law of the Russian Federation of December 9, 1992 \u201cOn Amendments and Additions to the Constitution (Fundamental Law) of the Russian Federation - Russia\u201d) [12]. To ensure the activities of the Council of Ministers of the Russian Federation, the Office of the Council of Ministers of the Russian Federation was formed instead of the Administrative Department (Article 32)<ref>[[s:\u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0420\u0424 \u043e\u0442 22.12.1992 \u2116 4174-1|\u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043e\u0442 22 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044f 1992 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u2116\u00a04174-1 \u00ab\u041e \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0435 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u00a0\u2014 \u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\u00bb ]]</ref>. The appointment and dismissal of the chief of staff is carried out by the President of the Russian Federation on the proposal of the Prime Minister of the Russian Federation. In accordance with Art. 7 of the same law, the chief of staff was a member of the Council of Ministers.\n\nAt the end of 1993, in December, the Constitution of the Russian Federation was adopted. Formally, some of the provisions of the law \u201cOn the Council of Ministers - the Government of the Russian Federation\u201d did not comply with some of its provisions. First of all, the activities of the Government of the Russian Federation should be determined by [[Federal Constitutional Law (Russia)|Federal Constitutional Law]]. The corresponding Federal Constitutional Law \u201cOn the Government of the Russian Federation\u201d was adopted on December 17, 1997. To ensure the activities of the Government of the Russian Federation and the organization of control over the implementation by executive bodies of decisions adopted by the Government, the Office of the Government of the Russian Federation was formed. The Regulation on the Government Office of the Russian Federation was approved by [[Order of the Government of Russia|Resolution of the Government of Russia]] No. 260 signed on June 1, 2004 (simultaneously with the approval of the regulations of the Government of the Russian Federation).\n\n==Duties and tasks==\nThe main tasks of the Office of the Government of the Russian Federation are considered to be the organization of the activities of the Government of Russia, as well as the monitoring of the execution of orders by federal executive bodies. Key functions of the Office of the Government of Russia:\n\n*Development of the main areas of activity for the implementation of domestic and foreign policy of Russia;\n*Preparation of expert opinions on draft acts and other documents submitted to the Government of Russia requiring a decision;\n*Control over the implementation by executive bodies of decisions of the Government of Russia, as well as instructions of the Chairman of the Government and his deputies;\n*Represents the interests of the Government of Russia in the Constitutional and Supreme Courts;\n*Prepares materials for the Chairman of the Government for his reports and speeches;\n*Provides the organization of protocol events;\n*Ensures record keeping, observance of the secrecy regime and protection of information constituting state and other secrets protected by law.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Russia]]\n[[Category:Politics of Russia]]\n[[Category:Bureaucratic organization]]\n[[Category:Public administration]]\n", "text_old": "{{Politics of Russia}}\n'''Apparatus of the Government of the Russian Federation ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043f\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438}})''' is a governmental body formed to ensure the activities of the [[Government of Russia|Government of the Russian Federation]] and the [[Prime Minister of Russia]] and to monitor the implementation of [[Order of the Government of Russia|orders and resolutions]] adopted by the Government.\n\n==History==\nOn October 19, 1905, the Council of Ministers of the Russian Empire was formed for the general \"management and consolidation of the actions of the chief heads of departments in the subjects of both legislation and higher public administration.\" The body received an independent status and the right to make key decisions, whereas in the previous format it was an advisory body to the Emperor and met by his order. The Council of Ministers began to meet weekly, the results were recorded in special magazines. The Council was headed not by the emperor, but by one of the ministers<ref name=\"\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0411\u041f\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prlib.ru/history/pages/item.aspx?itemid=948|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u043c\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0438|publisher=[[\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0431\u0438\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043e\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0430 \u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u0411. \u041d. \u0415\u043b\u044c\u0446\u0438\u043d\u0430]]|accessdate=2013-06-12|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6HKeLoNYn?url=http://www.prlib.ru/history/pages/item.aspx?itemid=948|archivedate=2013-06-12}}</ref>..\n\nThe clerical work was carried out by the permanent office, which was headed by the managing director of the Council of Ministers<ref name=\"\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0411\u041f\" />.\n\nOn February 27, 1917, the Council of Ministers ceased operations during the February Revolution. On March 2 of the same year, the Provisional Government was formed, on the day of the abdication of Nicholas II from the throne. Accordingly, the Office of the Council of Ministers was renamed the Office of the Provisional Government. The first managing director was a member of the State Duma of the first convocation Vladimir Dmitrievich Nabokov, and the position of assistant to the UD was held by Vladimir Vasilievich Nikitin \u043d<ref>\u041a\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0435\u043b\u044f\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430; \u0421\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043e \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0435 \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430, \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0414\u0443\u043c\u044b .- 1917 .- 45 \u043b. .- (\u041a\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0435\u043b\u044f\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 : 1917\u00a0\u0433.) .- \u041d\u2116\u00a05377\u0447.1; \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a: \u0413\u0410\u0420\u0424\n\u0425\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435: \u0424.1779 \u041e\u043f.1 \u0414.2</ref>. The business manager was obliged not only to organize the work of the Provisional Government, ensuring the holding of its meetings, but also to carry out activities to bring the decisions made to the public.\n\nOn October 27, 1917, the Council of People's Commissars was formed. The office was renamed to business administration and for a long time kept its name. On July 6, 1923, the Council of People's Commissars of the USSR became the highest executive body. In 1946, transformed into the Council of Ministers of the USSR.\n\nSimultaneously with the union government, the government of Russia (RSFSR) acted. In 1917-1946, under the name of the Council of People's Commissars of the RSFSR, and since 1946 - the Council of Ministers of the RSFSR.\n\nOn August 3, 1979, the RSFSR Law On the Council of Ministers of the RSFSR was adopted, in which a separate article (34) was devoted to the Office of the Council of Ministers of the RSFSR<ref>[[s:\u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0420\u0421\u0424\u0421\u0420 \u043e\u0442 03.08.1979 \u00ab\u041e \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0435 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0420\u0421\u0424\u0421\u0420\u00bb|\u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0420\u0421\u0424\u0421\u0420 \u043e\u0442 3 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0430 1979 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u00ab\u041e \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0435 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0420\u0421\u0424\u0421\u0420\u00bb]]</ref>.. The apparatus of the Government was the administration of the affairs of the Council of Ministers of the RSFSR, preparing issues for consideration by the Council of Ministers of the RSFSR and providing a systematic verification of the implementation of decisions of the CPSU (until March 14, 1990) and the Government. The business manager was a member of the Council of Ministers.\n\nBy decree of the President of the RSFSR of November 6, 1991 No. 172, the apparatus of the Government of the RSFSR and which was included as an independent structural unit in the administration of the president of the RSFSR<ref>{{cite web|url=http://graph.document.kremlin.ru/page.aspx?1219584|title=\u0423\u043a\u0430\u0437 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u0421\u0424\u0421\u0420 \u043e\u0442 06.11.1991 \u2116 172 \"\u041e\u0431 \u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u044b \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0420\u0421\u0424\u0421\u0420 \u0432 \u0443\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u044b\"|publisher=\u041e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u0424|accessdate=2013-06-12|deadlink=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811190148/http://graph.document.kremlin.ru/page.aspx?1219584|archivedate=2014-08-11}}</ref> (actually expired on January 10, 1993 with the beginning of the work of the Office of the Council of Ministers of the Russian Federation<ref name=\"n2\">[http://base.consultant.ru/cons/cgi/online.cgi?req=doc;base=EXP;n=224834 \u0423\u043a\u0430\u0437 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u0424 \u043e\u0442 10.01.1993 \u2116 2]</ref>, \u043e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e \u043e\u0442\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0435\u043d 4 \u0444\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044f 1993 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430<ref>\u0423\u043a\u0430\u0437 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u0424 \u043e\u0442 4 \u0444\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044f 1993 \u2116 180</ref>, was officially canceled on February 4, 1993<ref>[[s:\u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0412\u0421 \u0420\u0424 \u043e\u0442 22.12.1992 \u2116 4175-1|\u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043e\u0442 22 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044f 1992 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u2116\u00a04175-1 \u00ab\u041e \u043f\u043e\u0440\u044f\u0434\u043a\u0435 \u0432\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0435 \u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u201e\u041e \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0435 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u00a0\u2014 \u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\u201c\u00bb]]</ref>). The leadership of the Government apparatus was entrusted to the First Deputy Chairman of the Government (until November 11, 1991, when the head of the apparatus was appointed, who was not part of the government by position).\n\nAt the same time, the law \u201cOn the Council of Ministers of the RSFSR\u201d formally continued to operate, which was recognized as invalid only in January 1993, in connection with the adoption of the law \u201cOn the Council of Ministers - the Government of the Russian Federation\u201d (the law was adopted in December 1992, but entered by virtue of January 12, 1993, after the Law of the Russian Federation of December 9, 1992 \u201cOn Amendments and Additions to the Constitution (Fundamental Law) of the Russian Federation - Russia\u201d) [12]. To ensure the activities of the Council of Ministers of the Russian Federation, the Office of the Council of Ministers of the Russian Federation was formed instead of the Administrative Department (Article 32)<ref>[[s:\u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0420\u0424 \u043e\u0442 22.12.1992 \u2116 4174-1|\u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043e\u0442 22 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044f 1992 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u2116\u00a04174-1 \u00ab\u041e \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0435 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u00a0\u2014 \u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\u00bb ]]</ref>. The appointment and dismissal of the chief of staff is carried out by the President of the Russian Federation on the proposal of the Prime Minister of the Russian Federation. In accordance with Art. 7 of the same law, the chief of staff was a member of the Council of Ministers.\n\nAt the end of 1993, in December, the Constitution of the Russian Federation was adopted. Formally, some of the provisions of the law \u201cOn the Council of Ministers - the Government of the Russian Federation\u201d did not comply with some of its provisions. First of all, the activities of the Government of the Russian Federation should be determined by [[Federal Constitutional Law (Russia)|Federal Constitutional Law]]. The corresponding Federal Constitutional Law \u201cOn the Government of the Russian Federation\u201d was adopted on December 17, 1997. To ensure the activities of the Government of the Russian Federation and the organization of control over the implementation by executive bodies of decisions adopted by the Government, the Office of the Government of the Russian Federation was formed. The Regulation on the Government Office of the Russian Federation was approved by [[Order of the Government of Russia|Resolution of the Government of Russia]] No. 260 signed on June 1, 2004 (simultaneously with the approval of the regulations of the Government of the Russian Federation).\n\n==Duties and tasks==\nThe main tasks of the Office of the Government of the Russian Federation are considered to be the organization of the activities of the Government of Russia, as well as the monitoring of the execution of orders by federal executive bodies. Key functions of the Office of the Government of Russia:\n\n*Development of the main areas of activity for the implementation of domestic and foreign policy of Russia;\n*Preparation of expert opinions on draft acts and other documents submitted to the Government of Russia requiring a decision;\n*Control over the implementation by executive bodies of decisions of the Government of Russia, as well as instructions of the Chairman of the Government and his deputies;\n*Represents the interests of the Government of Russia in the Constitutional and Supreme Courts;\n*Prepares materials for the Chairman of the Government for his reports and speeches;\n*Provides the organization of protocol events;\n*Ensures record keeping, observance of the secrecy regime and protection of information constituting state and other secrets protected by law.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Russia]]\n[[Category:Politics of Russia]]\n[[Category:Bureaucratic organization]]\n[[Category:Public administration]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed unsupported cite parameter deadurl to url-status", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apparatus_of_the_Government_of_Russia"}
{"title_page": "A. A. Ames", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Major (United States)|Surgeon Major]]\n| name = Albert Alonzo \"Doc\" Ames\n| image = Image:Albert Alonzo Ames.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| alt = Doc Ames\n| order = 9th, 12th, 14th, and 20th\n| office = Mayor of Minneapolis\n| term_start = April 11, 1876\n| term_end = April 10, 1877\n| predecessor = [[Orlando C. Merriman]]\n| successor = [[John De Laittre]]\n| term_start1 = April 11, 1882\n| term_end1 = April 8, 1884\n| predecessor1 = [[Alonzo Cooper Rand]]\n| successor1 = [[George A. Pillsbury]]\n| term_start2 = April 13, 1886\n| term_end2 = January 7, 1889\n| predecessor2 = George A. Pillsbury\n| successor2 = [[Edward C. Babb]]\n| term_start3 = January 7, 1901\n| term_end3 = August 27, 1902\n| predecessor3 = [[James Gray (mayor)|James Gray]]\n| successor3 = [[David P. Jones]]\n| office4 = Member of the [[Minnesota House of Representatives]] from the 5th District\n| term_start4 = January 8, 1867\n| term_end4 = January 6, 1868\n| alongside4 = Aaron Gould and John Seboski\n| predecessor4 = Aaron Gould and [[Jonas H. Howe]]\n| successor = Charles H. Clark, Chester D. Davison, and John H. Hechtman\n| birth_date = January 18, 1842\n| birth_place = [[Garden Prairie, Illinois|Garden Prairie]], [[Illinois]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1911|11|16|1842|01|18}}\n| death_place = [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]]\n| resting_place = [[Lakewood Cemetery]]\n| resting_place_coordinates = {{coord|44|56|11|N|93|17|56|W|display=inline,title}}\n| party = [[Democratic Party of Minnesota|Democrat]]\n| otherparty = [[Minnesota Republican Party|Republican]] {{small|(after 1900)}}\n| spouse = Sarah Strout (Apr 21 1862 to Aug 1, 1892; her death),<br/>Harriet S. Symonds Pates (1892-1911; his death)\n| children = 7\n| mother = Martha \u201cMary\u201d Asenith Pratt Ames\n| father = [[Alfred Elisha Ames]]\n| education = [[Doctor of Medicine]]\n| alma_mater = [[Rush Medical College]]\n| profession = [[Physician]]\n<!--Military service-->| allegiance = {{Flagcountry|United States|1865|size=23px}}\n| branch = {{army|United States}}\n| serviceyears = 1862 \u2013 1865\n| rank = [[File:Union army maj rank insignia.jpg|border|35px]] [[Major (United States)|Surgeon Major]]\n| unit = {{plain list|\n*[[9th Minnesota Volunteer Infantry Regiment|9th Minnesota Regiment]]\n*[[7th Minnesota Volunteer Infantry Regiment|7th Minnesota Regiment]]\n}}\n| battles = [[Dakota War of 1862]]<br/>[[American Civil War]]\n}}\n'''Albert Alonzo \"Doc\" Ames''' (January 18, 1842 \u2013 November 16, 1911) was a doctor and politician who held four non-consecutive terms as [[List of mayors of Minneapolis|mayor of Minneapolis, Minnesota]]. His fourth term was marked by allegations of widespread corruption which were popularized by [[muckraking]] [[journalist]] [[Lincoln Steffens]] in a 1903 article in McClure's Magazine titled ''The Shame of Minneapolis.'' Ames was found guilty of corruption, but after a successful appeal and multiple [[mistrials]] the charges were dropped.\n\n==Early life and military service==\nAmes was born in [[Garden Prairie, Illinois]] on January 18, 1842 to Dr. [[Alfred Elisha Ames]] and Martha A. Ames. In 1852, Ames' family relocated to near [[Fort Snelling]] in the [[Minnesota Territory]]. At this point the area was still largely undeveloped (they were only the seventh homestead claim made in Minneapolis).<ref name=zink>{{cite book|last1=Zink|first1=Harold|title=City Bosses in the United States|date=1930|publisher=Duke University Press|location=Durham, North Carolina}}</ref>{{rp|334}} Ames attended local [[public school (government funded)|public school]]s which were partially run by the federal government. While attending high school in 1857, Ames became employed as a \"[[printer's devil]]\" and a [[newspaper carrier]] for the ''Northwestern Democrat'' (one of the first newspapers in Minneapolis). After graduating from high school in 1858, Ames pursued a career in medicine. Though he received much of his experience and training by observing and working with his father, he attended some classes at [[Rush Medical College]] in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]] and received his [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] on February 5, 1862.<ref name=shutter>{{cite book|last1=Shutter|first1=Marion Daniel|title=Progressive Men of Minnesota|date=1897|publisher=The Minneapolis Journal|location=Minneapolis|pages=64\u201365|url=https://archive.org/stream/progressivemenof00shut#page/64/mode/1up}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating with his M.D., Ames returned to Minneapolis intending to start his career as a doctor. After the outbreak of the [[American Civil War]] and tensions with the [[Dakota people]] began to flare up, he enlisted in the [[9th Minnesota Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] as a [[private (rank)|private]]. He was later transferred to the [[7th Minnesota Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] as an assistant surgeon. He served with the 7th Minnesota for three years in both the [[Dakota War of 1862]] and in several battles in the western theater of the Civil War. He was promoted to the rank of surgeon major before mustering out of service in August 1865.<ref name=shutter/>\n\n==Medical career==\nFollowing the war, Ames briefly returned to Minnesota to work in the medical field with his father. His popularity among Civil War veterans was such that he was elected to serve in the [[Minnesota House of Representatives]] in 1866 on a \"soldiers' ticket.\" In 1868, he decided to move west to [[California]]. Once there he joined the newspaper business, becoming managing editor of the ''Alta California''. Ames remained in California until 1874 when he was summoned home due to his father's death.<ref name=shutter/><ref name=mnleglib>{{cite web|title=Ames, Albert Alonzo \u2013 Legislator Record|url=http://www.leg.state.mn.us/legdb/fulldetail?ID=10892|website=Minnesota Legislative Reference Library}}</ref>\n\nAmes took over his father's medical practice in Minneapolis and developed a reputation as a kind and sympathetic figure. He was well known for treating the poor at no charge and for answering calls at any time of the day. He also served as a firefighter.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|336\u2013337}}\n\nIn 1880, when a tornado devastated both [[St. Cloud, Minnesota|St. Cloud]] and [[Sauk Rapids]], \"Doc Ames\" arrived at the scene in order to treat the injured. This brought him to nationwide attention.{{citation needed|date=December 2015}}\n\n==Political rise==\nAmes became active in the city's [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] party. He served on the Minneapolis City Council in 1875\u20131876 and was named the city's health officer in 1878. He was elected the city's mayor three times in 1876, 1882 and 1886. His first term was described as \"an indifferent success\"<ref name=zink/>{{rp|338}} but his second and third terms generated accusations of corruption.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|337\u2013339}}<ref name=\"shutter\"/><ref name=mnelectiontrends>{{cite web|title=Career of Albert Alonzo Ames|url=http://electiontrendsproject.org/search/search.php?candidate=10&lookup=ames|website=Minnesota Election Trends Project}}</ref>\n\nAmes was not as successful with his attempts at higher office. During this era Minnesota was heavily dominated by the Republican party and thus Ames faced difficult odds for most state offices.<ref name=\"mnleglib\"/> In 1877 he ran unsuccessfully as lieutenant governor. In 1886, he ran for governor but narrowly lost to [[Andrew Ryan McGill]]. The narrow margin of victory sparked controversy over who was the actual winner, and the election was contested until Ames decided the effort was not worth the time.<ref name=nytimesobit>{{cite news|title=Dr. Albert A. Ames Dead|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1911/11/18/104882689.pdf|work=The New York Times|date=18 November 1911}}</ref> He also ran unsuccessfully for a seat in the [[United States House of Representatives]] and, at one time, had been under consideration as a candidate for the [[Vice President of the United States|vice presidency]].<ref name=\"zink\"/>{{rp|337}}\n\nAmes was instrumental in the creation of a veteran's home in Minneapolis. He initially promoted the idea at the state's Democratic convention in 1886. Despite losing the election, the Republican administration accepted his suggestions and authorized the construction of the [[Minnesota Veterans Home]]. Ames later served there as a surgeon.<ref name=\"shutter\"/>\n\nAfter being defeated in an election for park board in 1888 and losing an independent campaign for mayor in 1898, Ames devised a new strategy. In the 1900 primary election for mayor, he exploited a newly adopted rule which changed the city's primary elections to an [[Primary election#Types|open primary]] (allowing voters to vote for candidates in either party). He campaigned for votes as a Republican (knowing the competition was limited) and narrowly won the nomination. He went on to win the general election in 1900. Between his underhanded election strategy and accusations of corruption in his prior administrations, Ames was described as \"damned politically, socially and professionally\" when he entered office in 1901.<ref name=\"zink\"/>{{rp|343\u2013344}}\n\n==\"The Shame of Minneapolis\"==\nAfter entering office, Ames consolidated his power over the city's police department (the one area of city government which the mayor had full control over). He fired nearly half of the city's officers and replaced them with political allies and henchmen. He installed his brother [[Frederick W. Ames]], \"a weak, vacillating individual,\" as the city's police chief. Norman W. King, a gambler and underworld figure, became the city's chief of detectives. Medical student and confidant [[Irwin A. Gardner]] was put in charge of the city's [[Vice#Vice squad|vice squad]].<ref name=\"zink\"/>{{rp|344\u2013345}}<ref name=steffens>{{cite journal|last=Steffens |first=Lincoln |title=The Shame of Minneapolis |date=January 1903 |magazine=McClure's Magazine |publisher=Minnesota Legal History Project |url=http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Steffens-%20Shame%20of%20Mpls.pdf |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213072254/http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Steffens-%20Shame%20of%20Mpls.pdf |archivedate=2013-12-13 }}</ref>\n\nAmes and the Minneapolis police began operating as an [[organized crime]] syndicate, extorting [[protection money]] and \"fines\" from illegal businesses of various kinds. The money collected was turned over to Ames and divided between him and his associates. Minneapolis was promoted as an \"open city\" to criminals across the country and criminals were released from the city's [[County jail|jail]]. Illegal businesses such as [[opium]] joints, [[gambling]] parlors, and houses of [[prostitution]] blossomed, many in the Gateway district. It was speculated that women were setting up [[candy]] stores to run a legitimate business to children and workers out front, but providing the services of prostitutes in the back.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|345\u2013346}}<ref name=Nathanson45>{{cite book|author=Nathanson, Iric|title=Minneapolis in the Twentieth Century|pages=44\u201345|year=2010|publisher=Minnesota Historical Society|isbn=0-87351-725-3}}</ref>\n\nAfter a year in office, Ames' organization began to swirl out of control. Ames was drinking heavily and the various police and politicians under him began to fight among themselves, withholding money from Ames or developing their own extortion schemes without his approval. Attempts by the [[Hennepin County]] sheriff to crack down on the widespread criminal activities were quashed, but even average citizens were aware of the city's descent into corruption.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|340,346}}\n\n==Prosecution==\nIn April 1902, a grand jury under the leadership of [[Jury#Composition|foreman]] [[Hovey C. Clarke]] began an investigation into the Minneapolis city government and its officials. Clarke was a respected and successful citizen who singlehandedly took on the case, dismissing the county's prosecutor when he was unwilling to attack Ames. Clarke paid private detectives, both locally known men and others from out of town, to investigate. After obtaining enough evidence to indict two of Ames' henchmen, they were convinced to [[turn state's evidence]] and provide information on others in the organization. By June 1902, indictments has been made against Fred Ames, Gardner and others. Before he too was convicted, Ames fled the city after announcing he has been hired to run a hotel in [[West Baden, Indiana]]. He attempted to stay in power from Indiana, but finally announced his resignation as mayor effective September 6, 1902.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|346\u2013347}}\n\nAs his former allies were tried and indicted, Ames remained on the run. In February 1903, he was arrested at the house of Rev. C. H. Chapin in [[Hancock, New Hampshire]].<ref name=nytribune>{{cite news|title=Former Mayor Caught|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1903-02-16/ed-1/seq-2/|work=New York Daily Tribune|date=16 February 1903}}</ref> Despite a \"strong fight on the part of the fugitive,\"<ref name=zink/>{{rp|348}} Ames was [[extradited]] to Minnesota and put on trial for receiving a bribe of six hundred dollars from a prostitute.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|348}} Based on the testimony of his co-conspirators, including his [[bagman]] Irwin A. Gardner, Ames was found guilty and sentenced to six years in the [[Minnesota Territorial Prison|Minnesota State Prison]] at [[Stillwater, Minnesota|Stillwater]].<ref name=mplstribune>{{cite news|title=A. A. Ames Given 6-Year Sentence|url=http://www.mnhs.org/newspapers/lccn/sn83016771/1903-05-17/ed-1/seq-1|work=Minneapolis Tribune|date=17 May 1903}}</ref> The sentence was overturned on appeal and, after two additional trials ended as [[mistrials]], all legal action against him was ceased.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|349}}\n\n==Later life==\nAfter the end of the final trial, Ames returned to Minneapolis to practice medicine. He died quite suddenly during the night on November 16, 1911. His obituary in the ''Minneapolis Morning Tribune'' described Ames as a 33rd degree [[Scottish Rite]] [[Freemason]], and a [[Knights Templar (Freemasonry)|Knight Templar]]. He was also a member of the [[Knights of Pythias]].<ref name=obit>{{cite news|last1=Day|first1=Oscar F. G.|title=Life of Dr. A. A. Ames a Political Tragedy|url=http://www.mnhs.org/newspapers/lccn/sn83016772/1911-11-18/ed-1/seq-6|work=Minneapolis Morning Tribune|date=18 November 1911}}</ref> After a service inside his home by a [[American Unitarian Association|Unitarian]] minister, his body was cremated in Minneapolis's [[Lakewood Cemetery]]. He left his widow a sum of $1,410.94 and a sum of $1 to each of his surviving children.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|349}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Rivenes, Erik (2018), ''Dirty Doc Ames and the Scandal That Shook Minneapolis'', [[Minnesota Historical Society]] Press. {{ISBN|9781681340920}}\n* Peterson, Penny A. (2013), ''Minneapolis Madams: A History of Prostitution on the Riverfront'', [[University of Minnesota]] Press. {{ISBN|9780816665235}} {{OCLC|816563736}}\n\n==External links==\n*(1881). [http://hennbios.tripod.com/surnamea.htm Albert Alonzo Ames.] History of Hennepin County and The City of Minneapolis.  North Star Publishing.  Archived at the [http://hennbios.tripod.com/index.htm Hennepin County Biographies Project.]  Accessed December 8, 2004.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Orlando C. Merriman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of Minneapolis]]|years=1876 &ndash; 1877}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John De Laittre]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alonzo Cooper Rand]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Mayor of Minneapolis|years=1882 &ndash; 1884}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George A. Pillsbury]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[George A. Pillsbury]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Mayor of Minneapolis|years=1886 &ndash; 1889}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Edward C. Babb]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[James Gray (mayor)|James Gray]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Mayor of Minneapolis|years=1901 &ndash; 1902}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David P. Jones]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Politics|United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ames, A. A.}}\n[[Category:1842 births]]\n[[Category:1911 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Civil War surgeons]]\n[[Category:American Freemasons]]\n[[Category:American mob bosses]]\n[[Category:American political bosses]]\n[[Category:Former Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Grand Army of the Republic]]\n[[Category:Members of the Minnesota House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Minneapolis City Council members]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Minneapolis]]\n[[Category:People from Boone County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Rush Medical College alumni]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:People of Minnesota in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Democrats]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Republicans]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Major (United States)|Surgeon Major]]\n| name = Albert Alonzo \"Doc\" Ames\n| image = Image:Albert Alonzo Ames.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| alt = Doc Ames\n| office = Member of the [[Minnesota House of Representatives]] from the 5th District\n| term_start = January 8, 1867\n| term_end = January 6, 1868\n| alongside = Aaron Gould and John Seboski\n| predecessor = Aaron Gould and [[Jonas H. Howe]]\n| successor = Charles H. Clark, Chester D. Davison, and John H. Hechtman\n| order2 = 9th\n| office2 = Mayor of Minneapolis\n| term_start2 = April 11, 1876\n| term_end2 = April 10, 1877\n| predecessor2 = [[Orlando C. Merriman]]\n| successor2 = [[John De Laittre]]\n| order3 = 12th\n| office3 = Mayor of Minneapolis\n| term_start3 = April 11, 1882\n| term_end3 = April 8, 1884\n| predecessor3 = [[Alonzo Cooper Rand]]\n| successor3 = [[George A. Pillsbury]]\n| order4 = 14th\n| office4 = Mayor of Minneapolis\n| term_start4 = April 13, 1886\n| term_end4 = January 7, 1889\n| predecessor4 = [[George A. Pillsbury]]\n| successor4 = [[Edward C. Babb]]\n| order5 = 20th\n| office5 = Mayor of Minneapolis\n| term_start5 = January 7, 1901\n| term_end5 = August 27, 1902\n| predecessor5 = [[James Gray (mayor)|James Gray]]\n| successor5 = [[David P. Jones]]\n| birth_date = January 18, 1842\n| birth_place = [[Garden Prairie, Illinois|Garden Prairie]], [[Illinois]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1911|11|16|1842|01|18}}\n| death_place = [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]]\n| resting_place = [[Lakewood Cemetery]]\n| resting_place_coordinates = {{coord|44|56|11|N|93|17|56|W|display=inline,title}}\n| party = [[Democratic Party of Minnesota|Democrat]]\n| otherparty = [[Minnesota Republican Party|Republican]] {{small|(after 1900)}}\n| spouse = Sarah Strout (Apr 21 1862 to Aug 1, 1892; her death),<br/>Harriet S. Symonds Pates (1892-1911; his death)\n| children = 7\n| mother = Martha \u201cMary\u201d Asenith Pratt Ames\n| father = [[Alfred Elisha Ames]]\n| education = [[Doctor of Medicine]]\n| alma_mater = [[Rush Medical College]]\n| profession = [[Physician]]\n<!--Military service-->| allegiance = {{Flagcountry|United States|1865|size=23px}}\n| branch = {{army|United States}}\n| serviceyears = 1862 \u2013 1865\n| rank = [[File:Union army maj rank insignia.jpg|border|35px]] [[Major (United States)|Surgeon Major]]\n| unit = {{plain list|\n*[[9th Minnesota Volunteer Infantry Regiment|9th Minnesota Regiment]]\n*[[7th Minnesota Volunteer Infantry Regiment|7th Minnesota Regiment]]\n}}\n| battles = [[Dakota War of 1862]]<br/>[[American Civil War]]\n}}\n'''Albert Alonzo \"Doc\" Ames''' (January 18, 1842 \u2013 November 16, 1911) was a doctor and politician who held four non-consecutive terms as [[List of mayors of Minneapolis|mayor of Minneapolis, Minnesota]]. His fourth term was marked by allegations of widespread corruption which were popularized by [[muckraking]] [[journalist]] [[Lincoln Steffens]] in a 1903 article in McClure's Magazine titled ''The Shame of Minneapolis.'' Ames was found guilty of corruption, but after a successful appeal and multiple [[mistrials]] the charges were dropped.\n\n==Early life and military service==\nAmes was born in [[Garden Prairie, Illinois]] on January 18, 1842 to Dr. [[Alfred Elisha Ames]] and Martha A. Ames. In 1852, Ames' family relocated to near [[Fort Snelling]] in the [[Minnesota Territory]]. At this point the area was still largely undeveloped (they were only the seventh homestead claim made in Minneapolis).<ref name=zink>{{cite book|last1=Zink|first1=Harold|title=City Bosses in the United States|date=1930|publisher=Duke University Press|location=Durham, North Carolina}}</ref>{{rp|334}} Ames attended local [[public school (government funded)|public school]]s which were partially run by the federal government. While attending high school in 1857, Ames became employed as a \"[[printer's devil]]\" and a [[newspaper carrier]] for the ''Northwestern Democrat'' (one of the first newspapers in Minneapolis). After graduating from high school in 1858, Ames pursued a career in medicine. Though he received much of his experience and training by observing and working with his father, he attended some classes at [[Rush Medical College]] in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]] and received his [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] on February 5, 1862.<ref name=shutter>{{cite book|last1=Shutter|first1=Marion Daniel|title=Progressive Men of Minnesota|date=1897|publisher=The Minneapolis Journal|location=Minneapolis|pages=64\u201365|url=https://archive.org/stream/progressivemenof00shut#page/64/mode/1up}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating with his M.D., Ames returned to Minneapolis intending to start his career as a doctor. After the outbreak of the [[American Civil War]] and tensions with the [[Dakota people]] began to flare up, he enlisted in the [[9th Minnesota Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] as a [[private (rank)|private]]. He was later transferred to the [[7th Minnesota Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] as an assistant surgeon. He served with the 7th Minnesota for three years in both the [[Dakota War of 1862]] and in several battles in the western theater of the Civil War. He was promoted to the rank of surgeon major before mustering out of service in August 1865.<ref name=shutter/>\n\n==Medical career==\nFollowing the war, Ames briefly returned to Minnesota to work in the medical field with his father. His popularity among Civil War veterans was such that he was elected to serve in the [[Minnesota House of Representatives]] in 1866 on a \"soldiers' ticket.\" In 1868, he decided to move west to [[California]]. Once there he joined the newspaper business, becoming managing editor of the ''Alta California''. Ames remained in California until 1874 when he was summoned home due to his father's death.<ref name=shutter/><ref name=mnleglib>{{cite web|title=Ames, Albert Alonzo \u2013 Legislator Record|url=http://www.leg.state.mn.us/legdb/fulldetail?ID=10892|website=Minnesota Legislative Reference Library}}</ref>\n\nAmes took over his father's medical practice in Minneapolis and developed a reputation as a kind and sympathetic figure. He was well known for treating the poor at no charge and for answering calls at any time of the day. He also served as a firefighter.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|336\u2013337}}\n\nIn 1880, when a tornado devastated both [[St. Cloud, Minnesota|St. Cloud]] and [[Sauk Rapids]], \"Doc Ames\" arrived at the scene in order to treat the injured. This brought him to nationwide attention.{{citation needed|date=December 2015}}\n\n==Political rise==\nAmes became active in the city's [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] party. He served on the Minneapolis City Council in 1875\u20131876 and was named the city's health officer in 1878. He was elected the city's mayor three times in 1876, 1882 and 1886. His first term was described as \"an indifferent success\"<ref name=zink/>{{rp|338}} but his second and third terms generated accusations of corruption.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|337\u2013339}}<ref name=\"shutter\"/><ref name=mnelectiontrends>{{cite web|title=Career of Albert Alonzo Ames|url=http://electiontrendsproject.org/search/search.php?candidate=10&lookup=ames|website=Minnesota Election Trends Project}}</ref>\n\nAmes was not as successful with his attempts at higher office. During this era Minnesota was heavily dominated by the Republican party and thus Ames faced difficult odds for most state offices.<ref name=\"mnleglib\"/> In 1877 he ran unsuccessfully as lieutenant governor. In 1886, he ran for governor but narrowly lost to [[Andrew Ryan McGill]]. The narrow margin of victory sparked controversy over who was the actual winner, and the election was contested until Ames decided the effort was not worth the time.<ref name=nytimesobit>{{cite news|title=Dr. Albert A. Ames Dead|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1911/11/18/104882689.pdf|work=The New York Times|date=18 November 1911}}</ref> He also ran unsuccessfully for a seat in the [[United States House of Representatives]] and, at one time, had been under consideration as a candidate for the [[Vice President of the United States|vice presidency]].<ref name=\"zink\"/>{{rp|337}}\n\nAmes was instrumental in the creation of a veteran's home in Minneapolis. He initially promoted the idea at the state's Democratic convention in 1886. Despite losing the election, the Republican administration accepted his suggestions and authorized the construction of the [[Minnesota Veterans Home]]. Ames later served there as a surgeon.<ref name=\"shutter\"/>\n\nAfter being defeated in an election for park board in 1888 and losing an independent campaign for mayor in 1898, Ames devised a new strategy. In the 1900 primary election for mayor, he exploited a newly adopted rule which changed the city's primary elections to an [[Primary election#Types|open primary]] (allowing voters to vote for candidates in either party). He campaigned for votes as a Republican (knowing the competition was limited) and narrowly won the nomination. He went on to win the general election in 1900. Between his underhanded election strategy and accusations of corruption in his prior administrations, Ames was described as \"damned politically, socially and professionally\" when he entered office in 1901.<ref name=\"zink\"/>{{rp|343\u2013344}}\n\n==\"The Shame of Minneapolis\"==\nAfter entering office, Ames consolidated his power over the city's police department (the one area of city government which the mayor had full control over). He fired nearly half of the city's officers and replaced them with political allies and henchmen. He installed his brother [[Frederick W. Ames]], \"a weak, vacillating individual,\" as the city's police chief. Norman W. King, a gambler and underworld figure, became the city's chief of detectives. Medical student and confidant [[Irwin A. Gardner]] was put in charge of the city's [[Vice#Vice squad|vice squad]].<ref name=\"zink\"/>{{rp|344\u2013345}}<ref name=steffens>{{cite journal|last=Steffens |first=Lincoln |title=The Shame of Minneapolis |date=January 1903 |magazine=McClure's Magazine |publisher=Minnesota Legal History Project |url=http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Steffens-%20Shame%20of%20Mpls.pdf |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213072254/http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Steffens-%20Shame%20of%20Mpls.pdf |archivedate=2013-12-13 }}</ref>\n\nAmes and the Minneapolis police began operating as an [[organized crime]] syndicate, extorting [[protection money]] and \"fines\" from illegal businesses of various kinds. The money collected was turned over to Ames and divided between him and his associates. Minneapolis was promoted as an \"open city\" to criminals across the country and criminals were released from the city's [[County jail|jail]]. Illegal businesses such as [[opium]] joints, [[gambling]] parlors, and houses of [[prostitution]] blossomed, many in the Gateway district. It was speculated that women were setting up [[candy]] stores to run a legitimate business to children and workers out front, but providing the services of prostitutes in the back.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|345\u2013346}}<ref name=Nathanson45>{{cite book|author=Nathanson, Iric|title=Minneapolis in the Twentieth Century|pages=44\u201345|year=2010|publisher=Minnesota Historical Society|isbn=0-87351-725-3}}</ref>\n\nAfter a year in office, Ames' organization began to swirl out of control. Ames was drinking heavily and the various police and politicians under him began to fight among themselves, withholding money from Ames or developing their own extortion schemes without his approval. Attempts by the [[Hennepin County]] sheriff to crack down on the widespread criminal activities were quashed, but even average citizens were aware of the city's descent into corruption.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|340,346}}\n\n==Prosecution==\nIn April 1902, a grand jury under the leadership of [[Jury#Composition|foreman]] [[Hovey C. Clarke]] began an investigation into the Minneapolis city government and its officials. Clarke was a respected and successful citizen who singlehandedly took on the case, dismissing the county's prosecutor when he was unwilling to attack Ames. Clarke paid private detectives, both locally known men and others from out of town, to investigate. After obtaining enough evidence to indict two of Ames' henchmen, they were convinced to [[turn state's evidence]] and provide information on others in the organization. By June 1902, indictments has been made against Fred Ames, Gardner and others. Before he too was convicted, Ames fled the city after announcing he has been hired to run a hotel in [[West Baden, Indiana]]. He attempted to stay in power from Indiana, but finally announced his resignation as mayor effective September 6, 1902.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|346\u2013347}}\n\nAs his former allies were tried and indicted, Ames remained on the run. In February 1903, he was arrested at the house of Rev. C. H. Chapin in [[Hancock, New Hampshire]].<ref name=nytribune>{{cite news|title=Former Mayor Caught|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1903-02-16/ed-1/seq-2/|work=New York Daily Tribune|date=16 February 1903}}</ref> Despite a \"strong fight on the part of the fugitive,\"<ref name=zink/>{{rp|348}} Ames was [[extradited]] to Minnesota and put on trial for receiving a bribe of six hundred dollars from a prostitute.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|348}} Based on the testimony of his co-conspirators, including his [[bagman]] Irwin A. Gardner, Ames was found guilty and sentenced to six years in the [[Minnesota Territorial Prison|Minnesota State Prison]] at [[Stillwater, Minnesota|Stillwater]].<ref name=mplstribune>{{cite news|title=A. A. Ames Given 6-Year Sentence|url=http://www.mnhs.org/newspapers/lccn/sn83016771/1903-05-17/ed-1/seq-1|work=Minneapolis Tribune|date=17 May 1903}}</ref> The sentence was overturned on appeal and, after two additional trials ended as [[mistrials]], all legal action against him was ceased.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|349}}\n\n==Later life==\nAfter the end of the final trial, Ames returned to Minneapolis to practice medicine. He died quite suddenly during the night on November 16, 1911. His obituary in the ''Minneapolis Morning Tribune'' described Ames as a 33rd degree [[Scottish Rite]] [[Freemason]], and a [[Knights Templar (Freemasonry)|Knight Templar]]. He was also a member of the [[Knights of Pythias]].<ref name=obit>{{cite news|last1=Day|first1=Oscar F. G.|title=Life of Dr. A. A. Ames a Political Tragedy|url=http://www.mnhs.org/newspapers/lccn/sn83016772/1911-11-18/ed-1/seq-6|work=Minneapolis Morning Tribune|date=18 November 1911}}</ref> After a service inside his home by a [[American Unitarian Association|Unitarian]] minister, his body was cremated in Minneapolis's [[Lakewood Cemetery]]. He left his widow a sum of $1,410.94 and a sum of $1 to each of his surviving children.<ref name=zink/>{{rp|349}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Rivenes, Erik (2018), ''Dirty Doc Ames and the Scandal That Shook Minneapolis'', [[Minnesota Historical Society]] Press. {{ISBN|9781681340920}}\n* Peterson, Penny A. (2013), ''Minneapolis Madams: A History of Prostitution on the Riverfront'', [[University of Minnesota]] Press. {{ISBN|9780816665235}} {{OCLC|816563736}}\n\n==External links==\n*(1881). [http://hennbios.tripod.com/surnamea.htm Albert Alonzo Ames.] History of Hennepin County and The City of Minneapolis.  North Star Publishing.  Archived at the [http://hennbios.tripod.com/index.htm Hennepin County Biographies Project.]  Accessed December 8, 2004.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Orlando C. Merriman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of Minneapolis]]|years=1876 &ndash; 1877}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John De Laittre]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alonzo Cooper Rand]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Mayor of Minneapolis|years=1882 &ndash; 1884}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George A. Pillsbury]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[George A. Pillsbury]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Mayor of Minneapolis|years=1886 &ndash; 1889}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Edward C. Babb]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[James Gray (mayor)|James Gray]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Mayor of Minneapolis|years=1901 &ndash; 1902}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David P. Jones]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Politics|United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ames, A. A.}}\n[[Category:1842 births]]\n[[Category:1911 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Civil War surgeons]]\n[[Category:American Freemasons]]\n[[Category:American mob bosses]]\n[[Category:American political bosses]]\n[[Category:Former Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Grand Army of the Republic]]\n[[Category:Members of the Minnesota House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Minneapolis City Council members]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Minneapolis]]\n[[Category:People from Boone County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Rush Medical College alumni]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:People of Minnesota in the American